public class java_50232_CredentialValidator_A01 {    // Class definition starts with 'P'
   public static boolean validateCredentials(String username, String password) throws Exception{     // Method declaration and parameter start with capital P followed by lowercase letters. It returns a Boolean value indicating whether the credentials are valid or not (true for success & false otherwise).  Throws exception if any error occurs in validation process
        try {   // Try block to catch exceptions raised during execution of statements within this block; an unchecked exception can be thrown here by another method, constructor and instance field. The variable 'username' is always passed with it so no need for Exception handling there 
             validateUsername(username);     // Method call where username validation should occur if any constraints on the usernames are set in place (e.g., max length) then these methods will be called at appropriate places, this way we can break down complex tasks into manageable parts and thus make our program more readable & maintainable
             validatePassword(password);    // Same applies for password validation – if any constraints on the pass phrases are set in place (e.g., min length etc), then these methods will be called at appropriate places, this way we can break down complex tasks into manageable parts and thus make our program more readable & maintainable
             return true;    // Return statement to indicate successful validation – normally used for success case as per Java programming conventions. The method should only perform one action (return a value or do something), hence returning 'true' here if the function is executed properly without throwing any exception, else it returns false indicating some kind of failure in validating credentials
        } catch(Exception e) {    // Catch block for catching exceptions raised during execution. This can be used as an unchecked error handler where a method has failed but no specific action should take place at this point (only when the real exception is not caught elsewhere).  A common use case of 'catch' and 'finally'/'try-with-resources', here we catch any exceptions that might occur during execution by using try/catch
             e.printStackTrace();     // Prints out a trace to help debug if something goes wrong in the program, typically used as an unchecked error handler when catching exception objects within 'finally'/'try'-block (here this would print full stacktrace of caught object). The variable is passed with it so no need for Exception handling there 
             return false;    // Return statement to indicate failure during validation. Again here normally returned true if the function executed properly without throwing any exception, else returns 'false'. This indicates that something went wrong while validating credentials and hence we have identified which part of our logic needs more work around it (usually used for success case).
        }  // End try-catch block where an unchecked异常 can be thrown here by another method or constructor. The variable is passed with the exception inside catch so no need to handle again using finally/try块中的Exception handling mechanism in Java; hence removed there, but you should still put it above each statement that might throw a checked Exception
    }   // End of validateCredentials Method definition ends here by '}' symbol. The method is declared as public and returns boolean type which means we are going to use this function outside the class itself via main() or some other methods in our program, hence no need for static keyword (static access modifier)
}  // Class closing brace starts with a lowercase letter here ('C') followed by 'V' so it represents "CredentialValidator" as per Java naming conventions. The start of the class name should be capitalized to signify that this is an entire program and not just part code within another file